ce:section.ce:para:
The chemical composition and properties of the homostructured nanocomposite membranes were identified through ATR-FTIR (Fig. 1
                        ) and XPS (Fig. 2
                        ) analyses. The FTIR spectra shown in Fig. 1
                        a depicts the characteristic functional groups of GO which are the hydroxyl (OH) stretching at around 3300 cm−1, carbonyl group (-C = O) at around 1724 cm−1, aromatic alkene (C = C) at 1625 cm−1, O-H deformation at 1410 cm−1, hydroxyl (–COH) at 1376 cm−1, and alkoxy or epoxide (C-O-C) peak at around 1060 cm−1. Due to the similarity of functional group and structure between GO and OGQDs, there were no distinct new peaks observed in the spectra for the membranes loaded with OGQDs. However, broadening of the hydroxyl stretching around 3300 cm−1 (Fig. 1
                        b) can be observed which may indicate changes in H-bonding within the GO sheets caused by the addition of OGQDs. In addition, the slight shift of the C = C or the unoxidized regions of GO at 1625 cm−1 and hydroxyl peak at 1376 cm−1 to a higher energy for the OGQD loaded membranes (Fig. 1
                        c) may indicate that a π-network was achieved [32] or simply that the OGQD and GO has physical interaction through π-electrons.

The thickness of GO must not vary too much considering that the specific deposition of GO deposited on the support was fixed at 2.5 × 10-4 g cm−2. The thickness of the GO layer is dependent on the deposition amount. As the specific deposition increases the thickness alongside increases (
                           Figure S3
                        ). However, the addition of OGQD into the GO made the lamellae thinner which indicates that interactions between the nanosheets was enhanced thereby creating a densely stacked layers of GO laminates. The changes in thickness or how loose the layer could greatly impact the pervaporation separation performance of the membrane as mass transfer resistance has a direct effect on the flux. That is, the thicker the selective layer will result to a lower flux.

Beforehand, the specific deposition of GO was firstly investigated in separating 90/10 wt% n-BuOH/water mixture at 25 °C to optimize and maintain the thickness of the GO lamellae. An additional mass transfer resistance was created when the specific deposition was increased alongside the thickness of GO lamellae (
                           Figure S3
                        ). Therefore, the resulting flux declined but the water selectivity increased (
                           Figure S4
                        ). The specific deposition at 2.5 × 10-4 g cm−2 achieved a flux of 757 g m-2h−1 with a water concentration in permeate of 99.2 wt% in separating 90/10 wt% n-BuOH/water mixture at 25 °C. Afterward, the homostructured nanocomposite membranes were tested at the same feed conditions as shown in Fig. 6
                        . It could be clearly seen that fluctuations in the total flux happened at varying loading amounts of OGQDs. The trend in the total flux could be directly related to the thickness of the selective layer previously seen in Fig. 3. The GO-OGQD100 membrane achieved the highest total flux with 945 g m-2h−1 with an exceptional 99.99 wt% water concentration in permeate compared to the pristine GO membrane with 760 g m-2h−1 and 99.21 wt% water in permeate. This directly shows the effect of OGQD on the enhancement of pervaporation separation performance. The OGQD possibly enhanced the interaction of the membrane with water molecules and permits the transport between the nanosheets faster.

Additionally, the high-water selectivity could be correlated with the interlayer space distance measured (Fig. 5
                        c and 

                           Table S1
                        ). The “empty space” which is the space after deducting the graphene thickness of 3.5 Å and the oxygen functional groups of 2 Å to the measured d-spacing values of the membranes [21,36]. The membranes at dry state condition have an “empty space” ranging from 2.93 to 3.09 Å and at wet state condition from 3.44 to 3.97 Å (
                           Table S1
                        ). All measured interlayer space, either in dry or wet state conditions, was found to be small enough to reject n-butanol molecules which have a kinetic diameter of 5.0 Å. While, the interlayer space can easily allow the water molecules with a kinetic diameter of 2.6 Å to permeate. This is the reason why the water concentration in permeate is observed to be > 99 wt%. The reason for GO-OGQD100 membrane achieved the highest selectivity (i.e. 99.99 wt% water in permeate) can be associated with the enhanced attraction of OGQD with water molecules. This just further proved that GO-based membranes are efficient enough to reject larger alcohol molecules and that the selectivity can be enhanced only by making the GO lamellae stable. Also, the addition of OGQD can improve the water transport.
